         <div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">

<ab><lb n="1"/>      <space extent="1" unit="character" dim="horizontal"/>  <persName type="emperor"><name nymRef="#Ἁδριανός">Ἁδριανῷ  </name><space extent="1" unit="character" dim="horizontal"/>  <lb n="2"/>    <space extent="2" unit="character" dim="horizontal"/> <w lemma="σωτήρ">Σωτῆρι</w> <space extent="1" unit="character" dim="horizontal"/>  <lb n="3"/>    <space extent="3" unit="character" dim="horizontal"/>    <persName type="divine"><name>Διὶ  </name><space extent="3" unit="character" dim="horizontal"/><lb n="4"/>    <supplied reason="lost"><space extent="1" unit="character" dim="horizontal"/></supplied>    <w lemma="Ὀκτωβρίων"><supplied reason="lost">Ὀ</supplied>λυμπίῳ</w></persName></persName>  <space extent="1" unit="character" dim="horizontal"/><lb n="4a"/><space extent="8"/></ab>
</div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>To Hadrian the Saviour Zeus Olympios.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>One of several small 'altars' dedicated to Hadrian:  <ref type="inscription" n="1277" target="090119.xml"/> (=81.98), <seg cert="low">
                  <ref type="inscription" n="1266" target="080256.xml"/> (=70.254)</seg>
            </p>
            <p>The title Zeus Olympios is thought to follow from the dedication of the Olympieion at Athens in autumn 129.</p>
            <p>The absence of a dedicator's name is unexpected.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="bibliography" n="none">
            <p>Unpublished.</p>
         </div>
